snippet.textDisplay:
The Arkansas Senate unanimously passed resolution SR 14, “to encourage the United States Congress and the Arkansas Congressional Delegation to work to end organ harvesting from prisoners of conscience in the People's Republic of China,” on February 28, 2019.

The bill was introduced by State Senator Bill Sample on February 12 at the 92nd General Assembly. The senate resolution follows an earlier house resolution, HR 1022, which was passed on February 18.


State Senator Bill Sample with Falun Gong practitioners at the Arkansas Senator’s Chamber (photo courtesy of Arkansas Secretary of State)
The resolution calls upon the Chinese government to “immediately end the practice of organ harvesting from all prisoners and prisoners of conscience” and “immediately end the ongoing persecution of Falun Gong and release all Falun Gong practitioners and other prisoners of conscience.”

It also calls for an investigation by the United States Department of State into organ transplant practices in China, the prosecution of those found to have engaged in unethical practices, and the denial of entry to perpetrators involved in these transplant abuses.

Furthermore, the resolution encourages the medical community to educate colleagues and residents about the risks of traveling to China for organ transplants to avoid unwittingly becoming involved in the killing for organs.

snippet.textDisplay:
No Sportsman that has had a long lay off ends up being the dominant athlete of their craft. The athlete that consistently competes and learns at the elite level for years and years, while being in the public spotlight and under high scrutiny from early on in their career till the end, ends up being the perceived best of their era or all time. Joshua has been in the spotlight and under scrutiny from the get go, competing against the top elite boxers and teams consistently since the beginning including amateurs and pros, Infront of large crowds for everyone to judge and watch, these are the sort of experiences that build a so called 'champion'.
Just look at the so called 'best' in other sports - 'Messi, Ronaldo, LeBron James, Michael Jordan, Federer, Nadal, Djokovic, Lewis Hamilton, Tom Brady, Tiger Woods, Sachin Tendulkar, Mayweather etc. All these athletes started competing at the elite level early on in their career till the very end consistently, while also being highly recognised and scrutinised, and learnt from years and years of consistent competition without layoffs in front of big audiences to eventually come out on top, they also all had rivals to help keep motivating them.
Joshua is the Number 1 in this era and always was going to be, his experiences determine it, you'll see!

snippet.textDisplay: All this  this frenzy and Euphoria over fury being  the best heavyweight boxer in the world is absolute rubbish. Tyson fury is an excellent boxer who moves really well for a man his size but he is not the best in my book until he beats AJ. Fury simply exposed Wilder who we all know was nothing but a one-handed puncher with freakish power and who was protected and hyped up as this fearsome, unstoppable killer for most of his career. Against an AJ who undoubtedly is  a far superior boxer to wilder  and has real knockout power, Fury wont find it easy. Don't forget that Joshua has shown that he's got the ability to adapt and rise to the occasion. So it should be great fight.
